{{Distinguish|Ohm's law|Acoustic ohm}}
'''Ohm's acoustic law''', sometimes called the '''acoustic phase law''' or simply '''Ohm's law''', states that a [[music]]al [[sound]] is perceived by the [[ear]] as a set of a number of constituent pure [[harmonic oscillation|harmonic]] tones.<ref>Ohm's law, ''n''.2, ''[[Oxford English Dictionary]]'', 2nd ed.</ref><ref>{{cite book | title = A Text-book of Physics | author = A. Wilmer Duff, editor | year = 1912 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=U_EzAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA530&dq=ohm+tone+phase&lr=&as_brr=1&ei=MguHR5ipHpnOtAPuwYDABw#PPA529,M1 | publisher = P. Blakiston's Son & Co | location=Philadelphia }}</ref>
The law was proposed by physicist [[Georg Ohm]] in 1843.<ref>Ohm, G., ''Annalen der Physik'' (1843) 59 513</ref> [[Hermann von Helmholtz]] elaborated the law into what is often today known as Ohm's acoustic law, by adding that the quality of a tone depends solely on the number and relative strength of its partial simple tones, and not on their relative phases.<ref>{{cite book | title = The Science of Musical Sounds | author = Dayton Clarence Miller | publisher = The Macmillan Company | year = 1916 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=7f8KAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA62&dq=ohm+tone+phase&lr=&as_brr=1&ei=MguHR5ipHpnOtAPuwYDABw }}</ref><ref>{{cite book | title = Lessons in Elementary Practical Physics, Vol. III, Part 1: Practical Acoustics | author = Charles Lightfoot Barnes | publisher = London: Macmillan and Co. Ltd | year = 1897 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=6TQIAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA160&dq=ohm+tone+phase&lr=&as_brr=1&ei=MguHR5ipHpnOtAPuwYDABw#PPA161,M1 }}</ref> Helmholtz championed the law in opposition to contrary evidence expounded by [[August Seebeck]].<ref>{{cite book | title = Combination Tones and Other Related Auditory Phenomena | publisher = University of Chicago | year = 1908 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=BUEIAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA128&dq=ohm+tone+phase&lr=&as_brr=1&ei=MguHR5ipHpnOtAPuwYDABw#PPA128,M1 | author = Joseph Peterson }}</ref>
The law has also been interpreted as "a pitch corresponding to a certain frequency can only be heard if the acoustical wave contains power at that frequency."<ref>{{cite book | title = Acoustics and psychoacoustics | author = David M. Howard, Jamie A. S. Angus | publisher = Focal Press | year = 2006 | isbn = 978-0-240-51995-1 | page = 123 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=Yyk5nAIJcBcC&pg=PA122&dq=intitle:Acoustics+intitle:and+intitle:Psychoacoustics+ohm+law&lr=&as_brr=0&as_pt=ALLTYPES&ei=5bxlSby6B5CQkQSJlpznAQ#PPA123,M1 }}</ref>
These laws are true to the extent that the ear is sensitive to the frequency and amplitude of the acoustic waves, and further, is able to resolve the differences in their frequency. In modern times, the sensitivity of human [[hearing (sense)|hearing]] to the phase of tone components has been extensively investigated.<ref>{{cite book | title = Loudspeaker and Headphone Handbook | author = John Borwick | publisher = Focal Press | isbn = 0-240-51578-1 | year = 2001 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=pAOFt1znYr8C&pg=PA655&dq=ohm%27s-law+acoustic+phase&lr=&as_brr=3&ei=NAiHR_CaNp6ktgP_i4zQBQ&sig=1OIFUWDCMTIUILOZrnaa5j3ef9M#PPA655,M1 }}</ref> Controversy has led to this characterization:<ref>{{cite book | title = Foundations of Modern Auditory Theory | editor = Jerry V. Tobias | publisher = Academic Press | volume = 1 | author = W. Dixon Ward | chapter = Musical Perception |year = 1970 | page = 438}}</ref>
{{quote|For years musicians have been told that the ear is able to separate any complex signal into a series of sinusoidal signals – that it acts as a [[Fourier analysis|Fourier analyzer]]. This quarter-truth, known as Ohm's Other Law, has served to increase the distrust with which perceptive musicians regard scientists, since it is readily apparent to them that the ear acts in this way only under very restricted conditions.|W. Dixon Ward (1970)}}
